nestedness in networks a theoretical model and some applications siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display nestedness in networks a theoretical model and some applications type siepr discussion paper 11 005 author s michael koenig claudio tessone yves zenou published 01 4 12 abstract we develop a dynamic network formation model that can explain the observed nestedness in real world networks links are formed on the basis of agents centrality and have an exponentially distributed life time we use stochastic stability to identify the networks to which the network formation process converges and find that they are nested split graphs we completely determine the topological properties of the stochastically stable networks and show that they match features exhibited by real world networks using four different network datasets we empirically test our model and show that it fits well the observed networks full text full text stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
